spanGrp.span: "Pear Story"; transcribed by ER in Ocotober 2009; OK, revised by WI in July 2013 for DoBeS project
hy sit (hulle) in die mandjie in
he puts them first into the pocket of the apron
sit hy eers in die voorskootsak in
(he) puts (them) into the pocket of the apron, (he) puts (them) into the pocket of the apron
ǀʼee ng voorskootsi ǁxaan, ǀʼee ng voorskootsi ǁxaan,
sit in die voorskotsak in, sit in die voorskotsak in
gooi hulle in die mandjie in
he fills the other basket, he comes and pours into the basket
ha ǂʼunn mandjiesi ko, ha saa ǂhaun ǀʼee ng mandjiesi,
die maak die ander mandjie vol, hy kom gooi in die mandjie in
he climbs up again, he takes (the pears) off
ha gǀoe ǁain, ha au ǁhuu,
hy klim weer, en hy haal weer af
a man comes and walkes past with ...
comes riding from this side with ...
kom ry van dié kant af met ...
he takes a basket, he loads (it) onto ...
ku ǀii mandjiesi, ku nǃao ng
hy vat die mandjie, hy laai (hom) op ...
the old man climbs down again from ...
a ǁhoen ǂoo gǀoe ǁhoe ng
toet die ou man weer afklim van ...
now he puts in again into the basket
toe kom sit hy nou in die mandjie in
sounds like [see], but E says it is and must be /saa/
(he) pours in again into then basket, (then) he sees
gǀoe ǂhaun ǀʼee mandjiesi, ha nǀii,
toe gooi hy in die mandjie in, toe sien hy
E translated /ǁhaa nǀaa/ 'hy het gesien', after some discussion she said it is the same lx as /ǁhaa/ 'eers' but the meaning here is definitely PST; try to check again and elicit
hy sit in die mandjie in
he rides, he rides, he rides, then he rides
ku nǃari, ku nǃari, ku nǃari, ku nǁae nǃaria,
hy ry, hy ry, hy ry, toe ry hy
a small young girl comes (again) from ...
E: /hoo ng ǁqhaanke/ 'kom van voor af'; /hoo ng ǃuu-ke/ 'kom van agter af'
then he looks at the young little girl, then he falls off, he lies
ku nǁae ǂaqe ǃʼoakera ʘuun, ku nǁae ǂʼaba ǁhoe, ku tyiin,
toe kyk hy vir die meisietjie, toe val hy sommer af, toe lê hy
the pears fall down, they lie (on the ground)
die pere val af, hulle lê
he sits and rubs his leg
sit en smeer hy sy been
(they) help him, help, they pick up, pick up, pick up, pick up the pears, pick up the pears, they put (them) into the basket
hui ku, hui, knn ǀii uu, ǀii uu, ǀii uu, ǀii uu peerke, ǀii uu peerke, knn ǀʼee mandjiesi,
help hom; help, hulle tel op, tel op, tel op die pere, tel op die pere, sit hulle (hulle) in die mandjie in
when speaking very slowly, E repeats [gǃai], in faster speeck it sounds like [gǃau]; it is definitely [ǁhoo] 'neersit' here, but E says both /gǃai ǁhoo/ and /gǃai ǃoo/ exist
he stands up, he climbs (onto the bicycle)
hy staan op, hy klim (op die fiets)
the other young man comes running
toe kom hardloop die ander jong man
(he) comes and gives him the hat
kom gee vir hom die hoed
E say PL of 'pear' is just /peer-ke/, not /ka peer-ke/, so the begin is maybe a false start only
(he) goes and shares (the pears) with the other children
loop ou hy die ander kinders
(he) gives a pear to one (of the boys), he takes (it), (he) gives a pear to one (of the boys), he takes the other pear for him(self)
aa ǃuu aa peer, ha ǀii, aa ǃuu aa peer, ha ǀaa ha peer ko,
gee vir dié een 'n peer, hy vat, gee vir dié een 'n peer, hy vat vir hom die ander peer
whole record is a little bit stuttered; E herself was not sure anymore if it is /ǀii/, or /ǀaa ha/, so don't use as example!
E could not explain the difference between /ǃuun/ and /dyaqnn/ and /ǁʼae/; but here, /ǃuun/ means really 'to go, walk', whereas the /ǁʼae .../ seems to be more grammaticalized
when they are close to the old man ...
knn nǁae nǂae ng ǁhoen ǂoo,
toe hulle naby die ou man kom ...
the old man stood up, he ...
toe het die ou man opgestaan, hy ...
they stood here, they were two
knn gǂunn nǃaaʼa ki knn gǂunn ǃʼuu,
hulle het hier gestaan, hulle was twee
/gǂunn/ is definitely a past marker here!!
not sure if /gǂunn/ is really there in this record
he looks at these children, he thinks ...
ku ǂaqe ǀoeke ngke, ku ǂʼiin,
hy kyk hierdie kinders, toe dink hy ...
it is certainly these children (who have stolen my basket)
but he looks, he sees them, (he) sees they walk relaxedly, they don't have anything
maar ku ǂaqe, ku nǀii, knn nǀii, knn ǂxain dyaqnn, knn ǁu ki gao,
maar toe kyk hy, toe sien hy hulle loop daar gerus, hulle het niks
E repeats /ka ǃqxʼora/, to me it sounds just like /ǃqxʼora/
he sees, no, it is not (it can't be) these children
ku nǀii, nee, ǀoeke ngke ke ǁae,
toe sien hy, nee, dit kan nie daai kinders wees nie
the children come and walk past
(they) pass him, he looks at them
ǃare ng ku, ku ǂaqe kike,
(hulle) loop by hom verby, hy kyk hulle
he sees, it is not them
hy sien, dis nie hulle nie
not sure if there should be an suffix on /dyaqnn/, E did not really like it
child which has rode the bicycle also keeps on riding
ǀoba he xa nǃaria nǀa baisikelsi gǀoe ǁʼoansi nǃaria,
kind wat met die fiets gery het het ook aanhou ry
these children keep on walking into this direction
a ǀoeke ngke ǁʼoansi dyaqnn ǁʼaa ǀxaa a,
die loop hierdie kinders anhou dié kant toe
